sons why this foundered. It considers the shifting nature of state policies towards courtship, relationships and attempts at family formation which subsequently became matters of class conflict. It goes on to explore the ways in which ideas about gender and family informed liberal and humanitarian critiques of the colonies from the 1830s and 1840s and colonial demands for abolition and self-government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConvict laborzAustraliazTasmaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPenal colonieszAustraliazTasmaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrisonersxGovernment policyzAustraliazTasmaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen prisonerszAustraliazTasmaniaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Australia & New Zealand.2bisacsh  aBritish empire.  aCyprians.  aTurks.  aVan Diemen's Land.  acolonial Australia.  acolonial authority.  acolonial order.  acolonial reform.  aconvict labour.  aconvict servitude.  aconvict transportation.  aconvicts.  agender.  aprivate sphere.  asettlers.  asexual morality.  asodomy.1 aReid, Kirsty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611859240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118592/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles